# VCF (Variant Call Format) — Complete Reference

VCF is a standard text format for storing sequence variations (SNPs, indels, structural variants). Developed for the 1000 Genomes Project; spec is maintained by GA4GH. Latest spec: [samtools.github.io/hts-specs](https://samtools.github.io/hts-specs) (e.g. VCFv4.5). Extension: `.vcf`; binary compressed form: BCF.

**References:** [Wikipedia – Variant Call Format](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Variant_Call_Format), [Genomatics VCF guide](https://www.genomatics.net/guides/vcf-file-format-complete-guide), [GATK VCF](https://gatk.broadinstitute.org/hc/en-us/articles/360035531692-VCF-Variant-Call-Format), [Intro to VCF (UW)](https://faculty.washington.edu/browning/intro-to-vcf.html).

---

## 1. File structure (order)

1. **Meta-information lines** — lines starting with `##`
2. **Header line** — single line starting with `#CHROM` (defines column names)
3. **Data lines** — one variant per line (VCF records), tab-separated

Missing data is denoted by `.`. Records are typically sorted by CHROM then POS.

---

## 2. Fixed columns (first 8–9 fields)

| # | Field   | Description |
|---|--------|-------------|
| 1 | CHROM  | Reference sequence (e.g. chromosome) name |
| 2 | POS    | 1-based position of first base of the variant |
| 3 | ID     | Semicolon-separated IDs (e.g. dbSNP rs IDs); `.` if unknown |
| 4 | REF    | Reference allele (one or more A/C/G/T) |
| 5 | ALT    | Alternate allele(s); comma-separated if multiple; `.` if no alternate |
| 6 | QUAL   | Phred-scaled quality: −10·log₁₀(P(ALT wrong)); `.` if unknown |
| 7 | FILTER | `PASS` or semicolon-separated list of failed filter IDs |
| 8 | INFO   | Key=value annotations; semicolon-separated; no spaces/tabs/semicolons in values |
| 9 | FORMAT | Colon-separated list of per-sample subfield IDs (optional; if absent, no sample columns) |

Columns 10+ are sample names; each sample column has colon-separated values matching FORMAT order.

---

## 3. Header meta-information

- **Required:** `##fileformat=VCFv4.x` (first meta line).
- **Common:** `##fileDate=`, `##reference=`, `##source=`, `##contig=<ID=...,length=...>`.
- **INFO definitions:** `##INFO=<ID=...,Number=...,Type=...,Description="...">`
- **FILTER definitions:** `##FILTER=<ID=...,Description="...">`
- **FORMAT definitions:** `##FORMAT=<ID=...,Number=...,Type=...,Description="...">`

**INFO/FORMAT Number:** `A` = per ALT; `R` = per allele (ref+alt); `G` = per genotype; `1` = one value; `.` = unknown/unbounded.  
**Type:** Integer, Float, Flag, Character, String.

---

## 4. Common INFO fields

| ID   | Meaning |
|------|--------|
| AC   | Allele count in genotypes, for each ALT (order as ALT) |
| AF   | Allele frequency for each ALT (from primary data) |
| AN   | Total number of alleles in called genotypes |
| DB   | dbSNP membership (Flag) |
| DP   | Combined depth across samples |
| END  | End position (e.g. for SVs/symbolic alleles) |
| NS   | Number of samples with data |
| MQ   | RMS mapping quality |
| SOMATIC | Somatic mutation (Flag) |
| 1000G | 1000 Genomes membership (Flag) |

Custom INFO must be defined in the header.

---

## 4.1. Phenotype-prioritization INFO block (pipe-separated)

Some WES/clinical VCFs include an INFO field that holds **phenotype-driven variant prioritization**: one block per compatible mode of inheritance (MOI), with pipe-separated values. The block format (as defined in such VCF headers) is:

`{RANK|ID|GENE_SYMBOL|ENTREZ_GENE_ID|MOI|P-VALUE|GENE_COMBINED_SCORE|GENE_PHENO_SCORE|GENE_VARIANT_SCORE|VARIANT_SCORE|CONTRIBUTING_VARIANT|WHITELIST_VARIANT|FUNCTIONAL_CLASS|HGVS|ACMG_CLASSIFICATION|ACMG_EVIDENCE|ACMG_DISEASE_ID|ACMG_DISEASE_NAME}`

- **RANK** — Prioritization rank for this variant under the given MOI (1 = top candidate).
- **ID** — Variant identifier (e.g. chrom-pos-ref-alt_MOI).
- **GENE_SYMBOL** — Gene symbol (e.g. FAH).
- **ENTREZ_GENE_ID** — NCBI Entrez Gene ID.
- **MOI** — Mode of inheritance (e.g. AR, AD).
- **P-VALUE** — Gene–phenotype association p-value.
- **GENE_COMBINED_SCORE** — Gene combined score (0–1).
- **GENE_PHENO_SCORE** — Gene–phenotype match score (0–1).
- **GENE_VARIANT_SCORE** — Variant support for the gene (0–1).
- **VARIANT_SCORE** — Support for this specific variant (0–1).
- **CONTRIBUTING_VARIANT** — 1 if variant contributes to prioritization, 0 otherwise.
- **WHITELIST_VARIANT** — 1 if from user whitelist, 0 otherwise.
- **FUNCTIONAL_CLASS** — e.g. missense_variant, frameshift_truncation (Sequence Ontology style).
- **HGVS** — Full HGVS string (e.g. GENE:TRANSCRIPT:c.974C>T:p.(Thr325Met)).
- **ACMG_CLASSIFICATION** — ACMG/AMP classification (e.g. LIKELY_PATHOGENIC, UNCERTAIN_SIGNIFICANCE).
- **ACMG_EVIDENCE** — ACMG evidence codes (e.g. PM2_Supporting, PP3_Strong, PP4_Moderate, BP1).
- **ACMG_DISEASE_ID** — Disease identifier (e.g. OMIM:276700).
- **ACMG_DISEASE_NAME** — Disease name (underscores in VCF = spaces).

Parse by splitting on `|`; index by the order above. Multiple blocks (e.g. one per MOI) may be separated by `},{` within the same INFO value. Use these fields for report text (gene, disease, ACMG classification, HGVS) without naming the originating tool.

---

## 5. Common FORMAT fields (per-sample)

| ID | Meaning |
|----|--------|
| GT  | Genotype (must be first if present). Alleles: 0=REF, 1=first ALT, 2=second ALT. `/` = unphased, `\|` = phased |
| GQ  | Genotype quality (Phred) |
| DP  | Read depth |
| AD  | Allelic depths (REF, then ALT(s)) |
| PL  | Phred-scaled genotype likelihoods (order as in spec, e.g. REF/REF, REF/ALT, ALT/ALT for biallelic) |
| GL  | Genotype likelihoods (non-Phred) |
| GP  | Genotype posterior probabilities |

Sample columns: colon-separated values in the same order as FORMAT.

---

## 6. Genotype (GT) encoding

- **0** = reference allele, **1** = first ALT, **2** = second ALT, etc.
- **`/`** = unphased (e.g. `0/1`), **`|`** = phased (e.g. `0|1`).
- **`.`** = missing (e.g. `./.`).

---

## 7. Special cases

- **Sites-only VCF:** Only 8 columns (no FORMAT, no sample columns); describes variants without per-sample genotypes.
- **gVCF:** Includes reference blocks and quality for non-variant segments; used for joint calling.
- **BCF:** Binary, BGZF-compressed VCF; indexable (e.g. Tabix) for fast queries.

---

## 8. Parsing and tools

- Do not rely on column order beyond the first 9; sample order is not guaranteed.
- Use established parsers (e.g. pysam, cyvcf2, bcftools) rather than ad-hoc parsing.
- Do not edit VCF in word processors (use plain text/editor only).

---

## 9. Minimal example

```text
##fileformat=VCFv4.2
##INFO=<ID=DP,Number=1,Type=Integer,Description="Total depth">
##FORMAT=<ID=GT,Number=1,Type=String,Description="Genotype">
##FORMAT=<ID=DP,Number=1,Type=Integer,Description="Read depth">
#CHROM  POS   ID   REF  ALT  QUAL  FILTER  INFO   FORMAT   SAMP1   SAMP2
20      14370 rs1  G    A    29    PASS    DP=14  GT:DP    0/0:1   1/0:8
```

When writing or interpreting VCF in this project, follow this specification and the official HTS specs.
